        <h1>LEARNING ABOUT SEMANTIC TAGS?</h1>
        <h2>TODAY I AM GOING TO LEARN ABOUT SEMMANTIC TAGS</h2>
    </main>

    <h3>what are semantic tags?</h3>
    <p>Semantic tags add meaning to your HTML. They tell both the browser and the developer what kind of content is
        being presented.</p>
    Here are some of the key semantic tags you must know about:
    <ol>
        <li>
            <code>"&lt;header&gt;"</code>Used to represent the top section of a web page, often containing headings,
            logos, and navigation.
        </li>
        <li>
            <code>"&lt;nav&gt;"</code> Signifies a navigation menu on a web page.
        </li>
        <li>
            <code>"&lt;articles&gt;"</code>: Indicates a self-contained piece of content, such as a blog post or news
            article.
        </li>
        <li>
            <code>"&lt;section"&gt;</code>: Represents a thematic grouping of content on a web page.
        </li>
        <li>
            <code>"&lt;aside"&gt;</code> : Typically used for sidebars or content that is tangentially related to the
            main content.
        </li>
        <li>
            <code>"&lt;footer&gt;"</code>: Represents the footer of a web page, usually containing copyright information
            and contact details.
        </li>
        <li>
            <code>"&lt;figure"&gt;</code> and <code>"&lt;figcaption"&gt;</code> : Used for embedding images, diagrams,
            or charts, along with a
            caption.
        </li>
        <li>
            <code>"&lt;main"&gt;</code>: Signifies the main content area of a web page.
        </li>
        <li>
            <code>"&lt;time"&gt;</code>: Used to represent time-related information, like dates and times.
        </li>
    </ol>
    <H2>
        <img src="semantic-tags.png" width="600" height="600" alt="differnces between semantic and non semantic tags?">
    </H2>
    <h2>
        Why Use Semantic Tags?
    </h2>
    <p>
        They enhance SEO, improve accessibility, and make your code easier to read and maintain.
    </p>
    <h2>
        Commonly Used Semantic Tags
    </h2>
    <p>
        Here are some commonly used semantic tags in HTML:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>header</strong>: Contains introductory content.</li>
        <li>
            <strong>footer</strong>: Holds footer information.
        </li>
        <li><strong>article</strong>: Encapsulates a self-contained composition.</li>
        <li><strong>section</strong>: Represents a standalone section.</li>
        <li><strong>aside</strong>: Contains content aside from the content it is placed in.</li>
        <li><strong>nav</strong>: Holds navigation links.</li>
    </ul>
